Patch Set 1:

Changing UNO commands is always a bit delicate. Wouldn't it be easier to just change label and character?

Patch Set 1:

Heiko: yes there were 2 alternatives, either changing the code (u'\x2060' to u'\xFEFF') or changing the English string in GenericCommands.xcu + change variables name accordingly:
https://bugs.documentfoundation.org/show_bug.cgi?id=140796#c8
but it seems alternative 1 wasn't right.

Between both alternatives, I don't have strong opinion, my only concern is to avoid a mixup between the variable names and what they represent.

Now there aren't public interfaces (at least no idl files changed here) but since I'm not a Uno expert, let's add Stephan to have his opinion.

Patch Set 1:

Julien, any specific reason you set me as reviewer?  Any specific part I should look at?

Patch Set 1:

Stephan: I put you in cc just to know if from UNO point of view it's ok (no compatibility pb or something I would have missed).
If it's OK, I'll push this one.

Patch Set 1:

> Stephan: I put you in cc just to know if from UNO point of view it's ok (no compatibility pb or something I would have missed).
> If it's OK, I'll push this one.

I don't know the implications of changing such .uno URLs.  (They are rather unrelated to UNO, some kind of a legacy misnomer.)

Patch Set 1:

Thank you Stephan for this new feedback, great news!

Heiko: ok for you then?

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Sure, fine for me. I wonder if use of ZWSP is also discouraged.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Thank you Heiko for your feedback.
Let's push this then.
Change has been successfully cherry-picked as b1cbc2e27a5a5434ca8097fa7586912cf0b857c4 by Julien Nabet

Patch Set 2:

> Thank you Stephan for this new feedback, great news!

I'm a bit puzzled as to why my feedback would have been "great news".  Don't get me wrong, I have not much insight into whether or not changing such .uno URLs has negative consequences.  (I think such .uno URLs can be visible at least to third-party code, maybe also to plain document authors.  This is somewhat similar to changes to the configuration schema, which can also have negative consequences on third-party code, and need to be weighed carefully.)

Patch Set 2:

Stephan: when I read "They are rather unrelated to UNO", I thought if there's no UNO impact, no pb here since it was the point Heiko was worried.
Now if I wrongly interpreted, feel free to revert this patch.

Patch Set 2:

>

Patch Set 1:

So I tried to understand commit 486d32f1e83002e6ff43db32463fb49393cc3664 and also make sense of the LOK poll function. Implemented this way we always poll, even for 0ms timeout.

Windows has the problem, that WM_TIMER / SetTimer has a minimum of 15ms, so we avoid sleeping by using it. But we never skip dispatching the main loop.

So I think this still does what tdf#131985 was about. But the real poll function looked very strange, always returning 0. I hope I understood all levels of redirection, but this needs some testing with LOOL.

It should fix Stephans problem, eventually better together with the 2nd patch in the relation chain.

It still survives sw.uicheck and sc.uicheck here, but then my original passed Jenkins and local magically too...

And Jenkins finally picked up this change - lets see, how that survives with some more CPUs...

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

(1 comment)

This looks like a really nice cleanup. I remembered reading that patch what it is there for; and perhaps worth putting in the README. In the Kit case - the poll callback itself can create and dispatch work itself including back via the LibreOfficeKit API - which takes the SolarMutex - and also handles lots of reading/writing/channel pieces. If we don't call that - bad things happen: we get carried away with running idle handlers all of which block further eg. input / user processing and life gets incredibly turgid for the end-user =) "complete idle layout before next keypress" eg. 
 Of course, there are potentially better ways to abstract and connect mainloops; really we should have a sensible API like glib's so other context's could be connected and polled and so on - but hey; also we care quite a bit about our polling loops' efficiency.
 Anyhow - looks like this should be ok to me.
 Thanks !

In theory we could run LO completely on the system event loop, as we just have a single timer which triggers the Scheduler on all archs.

Most importantly the LOK poll function now reports, if it actually did some work and LO correctly releases the SolarMutex before polling the system event queue / sleeping on the conditional.

Qt also has some abstraction for system event loops and uses glib on Linux as the system event loop per default.

So this fails again, but almost never locally :-( It looks like the main problem type I get is missing "objects" after closing a dialog. That is actually understandable, because the click just means the dialog closes, but at that point nothing has been done for the layouted document yet. As a result, the instant lookup of the new object fails.

Literally all python failures I saw have this construct, like:

    element = document.DrawPage.getByIndex(0)
uno.com.sun.star.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException: /home/jmg/Development/libreoffice/symbols/sw/source/core/doc/textboxhelper.cxx:284

And I have no good idea how to easily fix this with a correct solution.

Before this patch the SolarMutex was not released while the Scheduler was busy, so LO wouldn't process any commands from the PyUNO connection, until it was idle AKA for SW the idle layouter was finished.

In theory we "just" have to wait for an other OnLayoutFinished after modifications to the document. That is my understanding of one problem. But that would be a lot of work on all UItests.

A hacky solution might be:

diff --git a/vcl/source/uitest/uiobject.cxx b/vcl/source/uitest/uiobject.cxx
index 3c3d224024f4..f80a2bb8063f 100644
--- a/vcl/source/uitest/uiobject.cxx
+++ b/vcl/source/uitest/uiobject.cxx
@@ -16,6 +16,7 @@
 #include <vcl/event.hxx>
 #include <vcl/toolkit/floatwin.hxx>
 #include <vcl/menu.hxx>
+#include <vcl/scheduler.hxx>
 #include <vcl/tabpage.hxx>
 #include <vcl/tabctrl.hxx>
 #include <vcl/toolkit/lstbox.hxx>
@@ -622,6 +623,7 @@ void ButtonUIObject::execute(const OUString& rAction,
             return;
         }
         mxButton->Click();
+        Scheduler::ProcessEventsToIdle();
     }
     else
         WindowUIObject::execute(rAction, rParameters);

This is potentially dangerous for busy loops, where a Application::Reschedule(true) loop with some test would be better, but this can't be added to ButtonUIObject::execute, because I don't see a way to test for an expected result condition of a click, except LO being idle again.

I think just fixing the button "CLICK" should be enough. It would be better to expand the executeAction API, so the test writer could add a condition to the parameters, like
mkPropertyValues({"UITEST_CONDITION": "IDLE"}) or mkPropertyValues({"UITEST_CONDITION": "LAYOUT_FINISHED"}).
 
I'll upload a patch to see how far the dbgutil build can continue with this hack.

Any other ideas, comments?

Some more info in general; more then you probably wanted ;-)

It turns out UIObjectUnoObj::executeAction already does some kind of "ProcessEventsToIdle()": it first posts a TaskPriority::HIGHEST Idle, which then posts a TaskPriority::LOWEST and waits on a conditional, which is triggered by the low Idle.

But while hacking on it seeing deadlocks, I remembered commit ce8bbb782b806e429ffb44226162967bed244d94, which reminded me, that the whole "yield to main thread" can deadlock, if the "deferred yield" spawns a nested event loop. This can definitely happen for UI tests with modal dialogs. I'm actually wondering why it doesn't happen often; guess the busy, never yielding main thread prevented that out of pure luck...

I have a solution, but that just seems to work if I run the UItest via an external headless LO using gb_UITest_DEBUGRUN=T. Otherwise strange things happen AKA soffice.bin at some point just becomes idle in the middle of the test.

Then there is the problem of a nested yield running while in the Scheduler, which resulted also in a deadlock. Task::UpdateMinPeriod() is not allowed to run a nested event loop. That's just allowed when invoking a task. This deadlocked at least once when in SwDoc::StartGrammarChecking(false) took the SolarMutex, which triggered the DoYield... So while we want to unlock the SolarMutex in the yielding, non-main task to give others a chance to grab it, it seems we have to keep the m_bNoYieldLock "hack", just not related to the original intent.

In addition there is the whole mnModalMode stuff AKA "deferred yield from non-main thread with nested event loop, due to modal dialogs" deadlock of the yielding thread, until the event loop finishes. My current solution is to unblock the yielding thread before starting a modal dialog (it's a bit complicated for Qt; Windows has ReplyMessage and for headless you just must write to the "unblocking" pipe). We do something like this already on Windows with SetForceRealTimer, where we know a API call will spawn a nested event loop.

Obviously the best would be to get rid off all nested event loops in the long run. "We" are already working on that for WASM and LOOL. Both need non-blocking modal dialogs.

And there is eventually more I already have forgotten; and I know MacOS has the same problem. For gtk and X11 it's a bit different.
